Clearly not. The creature was content to whistle and tried to charge straight at Thassalin. Fortunately, despite his size, he was agile enough to dodge, but Nyssi couldn't help but scream when she almost lost grip on his too smooth scales.
"HOW DO YOU KILL THEM?", Nyssi shouted.
"AIM FOR THEIR HEAD!"
"THIS WON'T BE EASY!"
Thassalin blew, then made a turn to approach the mountain he called home. The black beast followed, somewhat frantic when a bolt of fire hit her from behind. The creature hadn't noticed that it was no longer alone. Her panic grew when Thassalin slowed down, then hit her violently on the head with his tail, making her deviate from her trajectory.
Growling and whistling, the creature took altitude and spat in the air. All of a sudden, everything became black, as if the monster was sucking in the light from the sky and replacing it with an eternal cloud of night.
Losing all visibility, Thassalin attempted to retreat, but skimmed the treetops before crashing into the clearing. As if she had exactly known where he had fallen, the creature charged straight at him, dragging the dark cloud in her wake.
"Kayel!", exclaimed Tenuk as he extricated himself from the cloud and began to fly in circles to try and spot Nyssi and Thassalin below, in the darkness. "What are we doing, Kayel? Kayel...? Kayel, where are you?"
Down below, Nyssi got up as best she could. She was sure she had broken something, but her unnatural healing powers had already begun to take effect. You couldn't say the same for Thassalin, who was lying on a mound, leaning against the only tree that hadn't bent under his weight. Nyssi did her best to try and reach Thassalin, but she couldn't see two meters in front of her. Everything was plunged into darkness, swallowed by impious shadows. And in those shadows, something was screaming.
A horrible club-like tail came crashing down next to Nyssi, sending her tumbling over. However, she noted that the tail was thrashing about, without aiming for her. The creature, from what Nyssi could see and hear, was growling and scratching at the shadows it had created. Something was teleporting through the darkness, striking the monster and disorienting it.
A shot suddenly resounded, and the monster collapsed in silence, inert. The darkness surrounding them dissipated, revealing what had just happened. Standing on the creature was Kayel, holding a rifle and panting for breath.
"It's... the most bizarre shadow leap I've ever made... Thanto kat'olon...", Kayel gasped. His eyes shone with a black glow, and a dark energy traversed his body. However, as he spoke, Kayel's organic plating regained its color, and his eyes returned to their normal yellow color.
It took Nyssi a moment to understand what had happened. They all knew that Kayel was endowed with strange shadow powers. He rarely used them, as most people considered them to be impious and rather terrifying. But Nyssi didn't know that Kayel could use these powers in the dark. And, judging by his behavior, Kayel seemed to be quite surprised himself.
"Are you okay?", Nyssi couldn't help but ask.
"Yes, I'm fine. I've killed something. It will be better in a minute." Kayel examined his work, while Tenuk made his way to land next to him, returning to his normal Spast form.
Now that the creature wasn't moving anymore, they could see what it was. Its skin was as black as coal and sticky, but the slobber continued to stick to its body. It had four wings and four limbs, all ending in long claws, and two straight horns protruded from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what this thing was, something howled and launched itself from a nearby bush. However, the beast wouldn't have time to reach them, as a familiar vehicle crashed into its side, sending it tumbling to Nyssi's feet. Not taking any risks, she grabbed her rifle and immediately shot it in the head, killing the creature instantly.
"Oops...", muttered Retvik from the driver's seat, before awkwardly cutting off the engine and jumping out of the truck. "I, uh, didn't mean to do that. Are you guys okay?"
"You almost missed the whole action," Tenuk regretted. "Where were you?"
"You all dropped me. I came here as fast as I could," Retvik sighed. "Can someone tell me what these dreadful creatures are?"
Retvik's questioning was fortunately answered by Thassalin, who had just gotten up.  He was all cut and scratched everywhere and seemed a bit disoriented, but he didn't seem to be too hurt.
"YOU KILLED THE CORRUPTIIDS! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. THE CREATURES LEFT HERE WHEN CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS."
"You mean... the terrible monster god that we've... helped to kill?", stuttered Tenuk.
"YES. RIGHT NOW. THERE MIGHT BE OTHERS, BUT I DIDN'T MANAGE TO HIT THEM IN THE HEAD. I'M MISSING A GUN. PLUS, TWO AGAINST ONE ISN'T FAIR, IS IT?" Thassalin walked up to Kayel and tapped his head. "THANK YOU, LITTLE ONE. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. BUT LESS MURDEROUS AND LESS ABLE TO KILL UNIVERSES."
"Uh... thanks... I guess", said Kayel with a shrug. "So, we're done, here?"
Nyssi shrugged, then picked up her camera to photograph the now definitely dead beasts. She then pulled out her favorite dagger, the one of the god of death, and began to cut one of the creature's horns, before moving on to the other. But just as she finished, the creatures ignited and quickly turned into piles of ashes. The same thing happened to the horns that Nyssi had cut.
"Well... it's both convenient and not very convenient at all", she sighed. "At least I'm left with the photos..."
